00:07:37.830 --> 00:07:39.900
During the first decade of governance

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:42.480
under the Constitution
of the United States,

00:07:42.480 --> 00:07:47.370
the young Republic confronted
a foreign policy crisis

00:07:47.370 --> 00:07:50.640
that fractured the body
politic and produced

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:54.170
an age of political violence in America

00:07:54.170 --> 00:07:56.010
as well as in Europe.

00:07:56.010 --> 00:07:58.920
The reign of terror in
revolutionary France

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:00.460
sparked the crisis.

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:03.400
And the ensuing wars of
the French Revolution,

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:08.400
which lasted from 1793 to
1815, sustained the crisis.

00:08:08.950 --> 00:08:12.710
President George Washington
issued a neutrality proclamation

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:15.800
in April of 1793.

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:18.700
But the American people were not neutral.

00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:23.350
Federalists just despised
the godless bedlam in Paris

00:08:23.350 --> 00:08:26.750
and prayed for fervently
for a British victory

00:08:26.750 --> 00:08:29.090
over French anarchy.

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:31.810
As feelings heightened Republicans

00:08:31.810 --> 00:08:36.810
were just as attached to the
cause of revolutionary France.

00:08:37.170 --> 00:08:39.950
And his feelings heightened
the partisan language

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:42.110
of politically active Americans

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:45.370
grew increasingly strident and extreme.

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:48.400
One theme common to everyone's talk

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:53.130
was the fragility of
Republic's in a hostile world.

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:56.010
And so Republicans described
the Federalists in power

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:59.700
not only as Anglophiles
but also as monarchists

00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:02.588
or monocrats, who intended to subvert

00:09:02.588 --> 00:09:07.340
the Republicans state of
Liberty and not only in America

00:09:07.340 --> 00:09:09.780
but everywhere in the world.

00:09:09.780 --> 00:09:12.070
Fantastic motives were ascribed

00:09:12.070 --> 00:09:15.660
to every federalist
initiative in the Congress

00:09:15.660 --> 00:09:18.470
and in Atlantic diplomacy.

00:09:18.470 --> 00:09:20.670
Federalists responded in kind.

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:23.150
They not only denounced
the Jacobin members

00:09:23.150 --> 00:09:25.230
of the Republican opposition

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:28.730
but also insisted often and vehemently

00:09:28.730 --> 00:09:32.970
that political opposition
when concerted and organized

00:09:32.970 --> 00:09:35.400
was equivalent to subversion.

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:37.260
And this was especially true

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:40.880
if it were orchestrated
by a foreign power.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:43.910
And as the nation inched
toward what we now call

00:09:43.910 --> 00:09:47.734
the quasi-war with France in 1798.

00:09:47.734 --> 00:09:52.370
Congress translated into law

00:09:52.370 --> 00:09:56.150
the Federalists' claim
that Republican opposition

00:09:56.150 --> 00:09:58.813
had put the very Republic in peril.

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:01.930
And so they passed the Sedition Act,

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:05.410
which is the heart of my lecture today.

00:10:05.410 --> 00:10:08.000
The Sedition Act made it a federal crime

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.307
and I quote, "To write,
publish, utter or print

00:10:12.307 --> 00:10:15.457
"any false scandalous
and malicious writing

00:10:15.457 --> 00:10:18.287
"against the United
States or the President

00:10:18.287 --> 00:10:21.787
"of the United States or
either house of the Congress

00:10:21.787 --> 00:10:24.057
"of the United States, with the intent

00:10:24.057 --> 00:10:25.887
"to excite against them the hatred

00:10:25.887 --> 00:10:28.207
"of the good people of the United States

00:10:28.207 --> 00:10:30.997
"or to stir up sedition among them."

00:10:32.890 --> 00:10:36.230
Now the Sedition Act has
the dubious distinction

00:10:36.230 --> 00:10:39.010
of being the only statute
enacted by Congress

00:10:39.010 --> 00:10:42.970
in the 18th century to be
declared unconstitutional

00:10:42.970 --> 00:10:44.960
by the Supreme Court of the United States

00:10:44.960 --> 00:10:46.880
in the 20th century.

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:49.430
In a case called New
York Times and Sullivan

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:54.430
decided in 1964 Justice William
Brennan performed the deed.

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:56.820
And there established what he called

00:10:56.820 --> 00:10:59.070
the central meaning of
the First Amendment.

00:10:59.070 --> 00:11:00.700
The central meaning of the First Amendment

00:11:00.700 --> 00:11:03.130
he said as he (garbled audio) old statute

00:11:03.130 --> 00:11:06.050
unconstitutional he said,
that central meeting

00:11:06.050 --> 00:11:08.390
was that debate on public issues

00:11:08.390 --> 00:11:12.230
should be uninhibited,
robust and wide open.

00:11:12.230 --> 00:11:16.650
And it may well be what will be included

00:11:16.650 --> 00:11:19.870
are vehement, caustic and sometimes

00:11:19.870 --> 00:11:22.980
unpleasantly sharp attacks on government

00:11:22.980 --> 00:11:24.333
and public officials.

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:27.690
Now at first glance at
least Brennan's description

00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:31.230
of the central meaning of
the First Amendment in 1965,

00:11:31.230 --> 00:11:34.770
sounds very much like John
Adams defense of free government

00:11:34.770 --> 00:11:37.790
in his dissertation on
the cannon and feudal law

00:11:37.790 --> 00:11:39.593
published in 1765.

00:11:40.650 --> 00:11:43.110
Behind Parliament's claim
to tax the inhabitants

00:11:43.110 --> 00:11:45.310
of the British colonies Adams wrote

00:11:45.310 --> 00:11:47.850
during the Stamp Act crisis of 1765,

00:11:47.850 --> 00:11:51.120
lay the divine miraculous
origin of government

00:11:51.120 --> 00:11:54.630
with which the priesthood had
enveloped the feudal monarch

00:11:54.630 --> 00:11:57.710
in clouds and mysteries.

00:11:57.710 --> 00:12:00.030
The thing said Adams had
always been different

00:12:00.030 --> 00:12:01.440
in Massachusetts.

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:04.220
Its government was founded on knowledge

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:07.423
generally diffused through
the whole body of the people.

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:12.470
Let every sluice of knowledge
be opened and flowing,

00:12:12.470 --> 00:12:15.130
said Adams in 1765.

00:12:15.130 --> 00:12:20.130
Let us dare to think and
speak and think and write.

00:12:20.790 --> 00:12:23.400
I said think twice, one of them was read.

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:27.673
Let us dare to read and
think and speak and write.

00:12:28.550 --> 00:12:33.150
The irony of course is that in 1798,

00:12:33.150 --> 00:12:37.433
President John Adams signed
a Sedition Act into law.

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:39.283
And there's more.

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:43.180
Neither Adams nor the house
and the Senate majorities

00:12:43.180 --> 00:12:46.700
who voted for it or the
Supreme Court justices

00:12:47.630 --> 00:12:50.200
who sustained it against
constitutional attack

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:54.320
13 different times between 1798 and 1801

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:56.800
doubted the competence of Congress

00:12:56.800 --> 00:12:59.183
to make seditious libel a federal crime.

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:03.750
In their view the Sedition
Act was fully warranted

00:13:03.750 --> 00:13:07.000
by the Constitution of the United States.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.540
Now describing how Adams
and the Federalists

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:13.513
reached this conclusion is my
first task in this lecture.

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:16.950
Three components of
the Federalist argument

00:13:16.950 --> 00:13:18.320
require attention.

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:20.340
First the Federalists had an argument

00:13:20.340 --> 00:13:22.040
about the scope of the First Amendment's

00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:24.260
guarantee of a free press.

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:25.870
Second the Federals had an argument

00:13:25.870 --> 00:13:29.280
about the inherent powers
of the national government.

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:31.490
And third the Federalists had an argument

00:13:31.490 --> 00:13:34.230
about the coextensive relationship

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:36.520
between the federal legislative power

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:38.910
and the federal judicial power.

00:13:38.910 --> 00:13:41.400
Now as I reconstruct this Federalist view

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:46.100
I hope that you will be impressed
by its logical coherence

00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:49.803
even if you aren't persuaded
by the arguments themselves.

00:13:51.040 --> 00:13:53.540
My second task is to account
for the nature and scope

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:56.780
of the Republican critique
of the Sedition Act.

00:13:56.780 --> 00:13:58.770
Culminating in the famous Virginia

00:13:58.770 --> 00:14:01.510
and Kentucky resolutions of 1798.

00:14:01.510 --> 00:14:04.730
And two years later in
Thomas Jefferson's victory

00:14:04.730 --> 00:14:07.560
over Adams in the election of 1800.

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:10.730
A victory that Jefferson
never ceased to call

00:14:10.730 --> 00:14:13.973
the revolution of 1800.

00:14:16.060 --> 00:14:18.450
It follows that my third
task is to describe

00:14:18.450 --> 00:14:21.560
the ramifications of
that revolution of 1800

00:14:21.560 --> 00:14:24.090
for American constitutional politics.

00:14:24.090 --> 00:14:27.090
And specifically for the
freedom of the press,

00:14:27.090 --> 00:14:30.070
for the Federalist
doctrine of inherent powers

00:14:30.070 --> 00:14:32.900
and for the Federalist idea of coextensive

00:14:32.900 --> 00:14:35.701
legislative and judicial power.

00:14:35.701 --> 00:14:38.300
In other words I don't need to explain

00:14:38.300 --> 00:14:40.420
whether the election of 1800

00:14:40.420 --> 00:14:43.210
generated a constitutional revolution

00:14:43.210 --> 00:14:45.260
as well as a political revolution.

00:14:45.260 --> 00:14:48.517
And if it did just how
extensive or how limited

00:14:48.517 --> 00:14:51.763
are these constitutional
changes turned out to be.

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:54.750
Now along this route it's my intention

00:14:54.750 --> 00:14:56.850
to establish some larger claims

00:14:56.850 --> 00:15:00.140
about constitutional thought,
constitutional practice

00:15:00.140 --> 00:15:04.910
and constitutional change in
the United States history.

00:15:04.910 --> 00:15:07.070
But you'll have to be patient.

